Name: Collins, Mike
text:
On this day in history in 1976, Operation Paul Bunyan commences as a show of force to North Korea following the deaths of two American soldiers who were killed while trimming a tree that obstructed their view of an observation post overlooking the Korean Demilitarized Zone.

The Korean Axe Murder incident took place a few days before on August 18 when a group of soldiers were pruning a tree planted by Kim Il-Sung. After 15 minutes of trimming, North Korea sent a truckload of soldiers to the site, who swiftly killed the soldiers with the axes used for pruning.

A few days later, Operation Paul Bunyan was carried out to cut down the tree rather than merely prune it. Task Force Vierra, consisting of 813 personnel, included 23 American and South Korean vehicles equipped with chainsaws, two 30-man security platoons, a 64-man South Korean special forces unit, 27 U.S. helicopters, several jets from both America and South Korea, infantry, artillery, and the 71st Air Defense Regiment. The USS Midway was also positioned nearby.

After 42 minutes, the tree was cut down. The soldiers left six feet of the stump deliberately standing as a reminder to North Korea.

This sham case, orchestrated by radical Democrat Attorney General Letitia James as part of her partisan witch hunt against President Trump, has been exposed for what it always was: a blatant abuse of power and weaponization of our judicial system to interfere in elections and silence political opponents.

From the outset, I have fought tirelessly against this injustice. As a proud New Yorker and defender of our Constitution, I filed an ethics complaint with the New York State Commission on Judicial Conduct against Judge Arthur Engoron for his inappropriate bias, judicial intemperance, and repeated violations of judicial ethics including illegal political donations by his staff and unconstitutional gag orders that silenced President Trump. I supplemented this complaint multiple times to highlight the egregious misconduct that undermined public confidence in our courts and turned this trial into a political spectacle. I also filed formal complaints to disbar our disgraceful New York Attorney General Letitia James for her blatant bias and highly inappropriate and prejudicial comments on social media related to this sham case. 

This ruling vindicates not only President Trump but also the countless Americans harmed by the Far Left's illegal weaponized lawfare tactics. Letitia James and her allies must be held accountable for their corrupt actions, and I will continue to lead the charge in Congress to expose and end this weaponization of government.

President Trump has always put America First, and the American people stand with him. We will not allow Far Left Democrats to subvert our Constitutional Republic. Together, we will restore integrity to our institutions, Save America, and Save New York.

I have reintroduced the One Subject at a Time Act, H.R. 4324. 

Congress must address its broken budget process, which has repeatedly led to massive omnibus bills and continuing resolutions (CRs) due to missed deadlines and a failure to go through appropriations in regular order.

H.R. 4324 will increase transparency for the American People regarding legislation, help restore trust in our representative government, and improve the federal budget process by focusing every bill legislators consider on a single subject, ensuring each topic receives a separate vote.

This is how it is done in Idaho, and I believe it is key to how the U.S. Congress can right America's fiscal ship and put her on a path of budget sustainability.

Name: Fitzpatrick, Brian K.
text:
Today is National Fentanyl Prevention & Awareness Day.

Fentanyl is not a distant problem‚Äîit is the crisis of our time. It is now the leading cause of death for young Americans, often hidden in counterfeit pills that look safe but contain a fatal dose.

‚û°Ô∏è Just one pill can kill.

Behind every life lost is a story unfinished‚Äîa son or daughter, a classmate, a teammate, a friend. Each tragedy leaves a family shattered and a community forever changed.

As Co-Chair of the Bipartisan Mental Health & Substance Use Disorder Task Force, I am continuing my work to change that by:

‚úÖ Driving nationwide prevention efforts to educate teens and families and cut through the silence and stigma
‚úÖ Forging partnerships with schools, healthcare providers, and law enforcement so communities are equipped to act
‚úÖ Delivering federal resources to expand treatment, recovery, and life-saving tools for families on the frontlines
‚úÖ Advancing bipartisan legislation to crack down on counterfeit pills, hold traffickers accountable, expand prevention, and save lives

But prevention must also begin at home:

üõë Talk openly about the dangers of fentanyl and counterfeit pills
üõë Never share or take someone else‚Äôs medication
üõë Store prescriptions securely and out of reach of children, teens, and pets
üõë Safely dispose of unused medications through FDA or DEA take-back programs to prevent misuse
üõë Know the warning signs of an overdose‚Äîclammy skin, blue lips or fingertips, gurgling noises, or slowed breathing‚Äîand call 911 immediately

This is a fight for our children, our families, and our communities. I will not stop until we turn the tide on fentanyl and give every community the resources to overcome this epidemic.

Name: Cuellar, Henry
text:
The deployment of an Aerostat in Zapata County is part of a program that enhances security, improves situational awareness, and optimizes resource allocation across the southern border.

Flying at 3,000 feet, the Aerostat serves as a visible ‚Äúeye in the sky,‚Äù acting as a strong deterrent to smugglers and illegal border crossers. With real-time, wide-area surveillance that covers 20 miles of border, agents can better detect and deter illicit activity, close technology gaps, and allocate resources more effectively.

I was pleased to work in a bipartisan manner with my friend and colleague @RepMcCaul to help launch this important program, strengthening security and providing more comprehensive coverage along the southern border.

The results are clear ‚Äì in FY25, nearby zones averaged 11 gotaways per month. Since the Aerostat was deployed, those same areas have seen zero. I‚Äôll continue to work across the aisle to find ways to help secure the southern border.

Name: Palmer, Gary J.
text:
I was very saddened to hear of the passing of Dr. James Dobson. Dr. Dobson was certainly one of the most influential leaders in America in the last century. Dr. Dobson had a major impact on Ann and me and our children. We first became aware of Dr. Dobson in the mid-1980s at our church through a video series of his lessons on marriage and child rearing. 

Later, in 1989, I was one of a small group of people chosen to participate in a special conference at the Focus on Family headquarters that led to the founding of the Alabama Family Alliance, that later became the Alabama Policy Institute, as part of a national network of family policy councils. In that regard, Dr. Dobson has had a huge impact in Alabama.

I last talked with him in May and had a chance to thank him for all he has meant to countless millions of people and to my family and me. He was, without question, one of the most influential American leaders in the last 50 years whose voice impacted the lives of millions of families promoting a culture based on the biblical values needed to sustain our nation at a time when those values have been under relentless attack. His more than 70 books and weekday radio broadcast covered the full spectrum of marriage and family from couples just starting out to finishing well in our later years. Dr. Dobson lived what he wrote and spoke about; he finished well. 

Ann and I are praying for his wife Shirley, their children, their grandchildren, and that God will give them comfort and that they will feel the gratitude of all who were so blessed by Dr. Dobson‚Äôs ministry.

Name: Collins, Mike
text:
On this day in history in 1992, the infamous Ruby Ridge standoff continued. 

Randy Weaver and his family lived atop a mountain in remote Ruby Ridge, Idaho. Weaver was targeted by the government after selling two sawed-off shotguns to an Alcohol, Tobacco, and Firearm (ATF) informant working to catch him. Weaver was let off on bail but failed to appear at court after his defense provided him with the wrong court date. 

After this, ATF handed the case over to the US Marshals, who began surveillance on Weaver and his property by installing various cameras. On August 21, Weaver, his friend, Kevin Harris, his 14 year-old son, Sammy, chased after their dog, Striker, on the family property. They came across an armed, camouflaged man who failed to state that he was a federal agent. The marshal shot and killed the dog before pointing his gun at Sammy, causing Sammy to shoot at the marshal. Sammy was shot in the back while running away from the unmarked agent.

The Weaver family refused to surrender, and the standoff began. The US Marshals then handed the case to the FBI, conveying that a militia group killed a federal agent. Neighbors were evacuated from their homes, roads near Ruby Ridge were closed, and the governor declared a state of emergency. 

The next day, an FBI sniper 200 yards away shot and wounded Weaver and Harris and fatally shot his wife, Vicki Weaver, who was holding their infant daughter.

Nine days later, on August 31, Harris, Weaver, and his three daughters surrendered.

Weaver was initially tried, but was acquitted on all charges except for the original charges of the violation of bail and failure to appear. Weaver filed a civil lawsuit and won over $3 million.

Name: Fitzpatrick, Brian K.
text:
Each week, we share stories from across our district of individuals who use their talents to strengthen our community and our country‚Äîand who make us proud to call Bucks County home. Today, we shine a light on one of our own who has risen to the very top of his field while never forgetting where he came from. Meet this week‚Äôs Hometown Hero, Robert ‚ÄúBob‚Äù Costa of Lower Makefield.
 
Bob has just been named this year‚Äôs recipient of the National Press Club‚Äôs prestigious Fourth Estate Award‚Äîthe highest honor in American journalism. It is reserved for those whose work has changed the way we understand our democracy and the institutions that shape it. And now, alongside legends like Walter Cronkite, Andrea Mitchell, and Tom Brokaw, stands a proud graduate of Pennsbury High School.
 
From editing the school paper and serving as senior class president, even landing John Mayer to play the senior prom, to covering music for the Bucks County Courier Times and interning with my late brother, Mike Fitzpatrick, Bob‚Äôs story has always been rooted here at home. He went on to the Washington Post, co-authored a best-selling book with Bob Woodward, and today serves as a national correspondent for CBS Sunday Morning and chief Washington analyst for CBS News.
 
But what makes this honor so meaningful is not only Bob‚Äôs remarkable career, but how he‚Äôs carried Bucks County with him every step of the way. Growing up here, surrounded by neighbors with so many different perspectives, taught him to listen first. As he‚Äôs said: ‚ÄúPeople can, in good faith, have different perspectives. You have to listen to your neighbor and not expect that everyone has the same view.‚Äù I share that belief. It‚Äôs at the heart of who we are in Bucks County: disagreement does not have to mean division, and listening is the foundation of both democracy and community.
 
From Pennsbury‚Äôs classrooms to the halls of CBS News, Bob has carried that spirit with him‚Äîand today, the nation honors it with journalism‚Äôs highest prize.
 
Please join me in congratulating @costareports on this well-deserved recognition‚Äîand in thanking him for continuing to make Bucks County proud.

Name: Cuellar, Henry

üì¢National crime statistics confirm what South Texans have long known: our border communities are among the safest in the country.

The 2024 Uniform Crime Report shows violent crime and murder rates in cities like Laredo and Rio Grande City are far lower than the national average and dramatically below many large U.S. cities.

For example, Detroit recorded a murder rate of 31.17 per 100,000 residents. Baltimore, 34.8.

In Laredo, the rate was 2.32 and in Rio Grande City, zero.

Safety is more than a number ‚Äì it‚Äôs families walking to church with peace of mind, parents sending their kids to school, and workers heading to the job site knowing their community is secure.

That‚Äôs why I‚Äôll continue fighting to ensure our law enforcement officers have the resources they need to protect South Texas and keep our communities strong.

Name: Bentz, Cliff
text:
Last week, the Oregon Nurse‚Äôs Association held a meeting in Madras to discuss the impact of the ‚ÄúOne Big Beautiful Bill‚Äù (OBBB) on the Madras hospital. This meeting was attended by one of my Oregon congressional Democratic colleagues. At the meeting it was apparently said that the OBBB would cause the closure of the Madras Hospital. This statement has caused distress. To get the facts, I met today and yesterday with the hospital‚Äôs leadership. Also in attendance was Jefferson County Commissioner Kelly Semmilink. They made it absolutely clear that St. Charles Madras is NOT closing, is in no danger whatsoever of closing, and that they strongly believe, for excellent reasons, that the St. Charles‚Äô system will manage just fine through the changes imposed by the OBBB.
 
They assured me that St. Charles has been and remains committed to continue providing access to quality care across Central Oregon. 
 
I look forward to continuing to work closely with the St. Charles leadership team to ensure St. Charles Madras remains strong and continues serving the Central Oregon community for years to come.

Name: Levin, Mike
text: I am closely following reports of another ICE arrest this morning in Encinitas. If an individual poses a genuine threat to public safety and has a lawful removal order, they can and should be detained and subject to due process. But I continue to have serious concerns.

Name: Levin, Mike
text: Specifically, ICE‚Äôs stated mission is to protect national security and public safety. That mission does not justify creating fear in neighborhoods or carrying out operations without transparency. Federal officers should identify themselves in ways that confirm their authority, and the public has a right to expect that clarity. Due process and limits on the use of force are not optional; they are constitutional requirements. I continue to demand that enforcement actions avoid areas near schools and places of worship unless there is no other way to protect public safety.

Name: Levin, Mike
text: I commend the City of Encinitas for responding swiftly and unanimously after the events of the past week. The City Council voted to launch a bilingual Know Your Rights campaign, to file a Freedom of Information Act request on ICE operations, to examine establishing safe zones at schools and houses of worship, and to demand answers from federal agencies in a public forum. I will do whatever I can to help them achieve these goals. These documented steps show leadership that prioritizes clarity, transparency, and accountability for the people they represent.

Name: Levin, Mike

Name: Greene, Marjorie Taylor
text:
If America was being bombed day and night because of something horrific our government did, and many innocent Americans and American children were being killed and traumatically injured, and we begged for mercy, but the rest of the world said, 

‚ÄúAmericans voted for their government so they deserve it, their government is bad so all Americans are bad, therefore this is what they get and must be done‚Äù 

And the world was silent to our suffering.

And no one came to our aid.

And our cities and homes were bombed and turned to rubble.

And our infrastructure was destroyed, no farms, no grocery stores, no more organized society.

And no one helped our injured and hungry children.

How would you feel?

What would you think? 

What would you do?

This is what is happening to Gaza where in spite of what we have all been told, many innocent people and children are being killed and they are not Hamas.

Does Hamas deserve it? Yes.

Do innocent people and children deserve it? No.

The innocent people in Gaza did not kill and kidnap the innocent people in Israel on Oct 7th. 

Just as we spoke out and had compassion for the victims and families of Oct7, how can Americans not speak out and have compassion for the masses of innocent people and children in Gaza?

Is one type of innocent life worthy and another type of innocent life worth nothing?

For me, I think God sees all innocent lives the same and he loves them all. As a matter of fact, He sent his own son for all people, that‚Äôs how much He loves us.

America funds Israel $3.8 billion annually for military aid.

Actually correction.

U.S. taxpayers fund Israel $3.8 billion annually for military aid.

That means every U.S. tax payer is contributing to Israel‚Äôs military actions.

I don‚Äôt know about you, but I don‚Äôt want to pay for genocide in a foreign country against a foreign people for a foreign war that I had nothing to do with.

And I will not be silent about it.

Name: Collins, Mike
text:
On this day in history in 1943, the Battle of Kursk, the largest tank battle in warfare history, ends after 50 days. 

The Battle of Kursk, fought in southwestern Russia, was a major clash between Germany and the Soviet Union, culminating in a Soviet victory. This battle, the largest of World War II is often regarded as a key turning point in the war. 

Known for its intense and costly nature, it‚Äôs the deadliest armored engagement in history and saw the opening day, July 5, become the most lethal day in aerial warfare. The confrontation began with Germany's Operation Citadel, aimed at encircling the Kursk salient through simultaneous assaults from the north and south. 

The battle was characterized by brutal house-to-house and hand-to-hand combat, involving 6,000 tanks, 2,000,000 troops, and 4,000 aircraft.

text:
I was pleased to join families, community leaders, Councilwoman Cigarroa, Dr. Martinez, and the dedicated team at Roots Recovery for Anthony‚Äôs Block Party last night during Overdose Prevention Month. This event was a powerful reminder that saving lives and supporting our neighbors is something we must do together.

This event was a powerful reminder that saving lives and supporting our neighbors is something we must do together. Roots Recovery is leading the way here in Laredo, providing life-saving detox care, counseling, and medical support to hundreds of people who otherwise would have nowhere to turn. 

That is why I worked to secure $2 million in federal funding to help them hire staff, purchase equipment, and expand their services. Because of their efforts, overdose deaths in Laredo have dropped by more than half, the first decline since 2017.

We remembered those we have lost, stood with those still fighting, and renewed our commitment to building a community where no one has to struggle alone. I will continue working to support Roots Recovery and all the organizations that are giving hope and saving lives in our community.

text:
On this day in history in 2012, Voyager 1 became the first spacecraft to enter interstellar space.

Launched in 1977, it was originally designed to study Jupiter and Saturn. After completing that, it continued traveling at 38,000 miles per hour, eventually entering interstellar space, 12 billion miles from Earth. 

Today, Voyager 1 continues drifting through the Milky Way while sending back valuable data. It also carries the Golden Record, a time capsule containing sounds, music, and greetings from Earth meant as a message to any intelligent beings who may encounter it.

Name: Rulli, Michael A.
text:
Today, I had the honor of formally presenting long-overdue medals to the family of WWII hero Daniel Hall, a young man who never returned home and whose service went unrecognized for decades. Private Hall was drafted into the military directly out of high school, and in September 1944, he was declared Missing in Action and later Killed in Action. Thanks to the perseverance of his loved ones and the diligent work of our staff, his ultimate sacrifice is now rightfully honored.

Among the decorations presented were the Bronze Star Medal, Purple Heart, European-African-Middle Eastern Campaign Medal, World War II Victory Medal, Combat Infantryman Badge (1st Award), and the Honorable Service Lapel Button (WWII).

Name: Costa, Jim
text:
Dr. Joseph I. Castro dedicated his life to expanding opportunity through education. A grandson of immigrants, his story is the American story. Raised by a single mother, Joe grew up in Hanford, California, and was the first in his family to graduate from college. He knew his journey reflected the story of so many in the Valley striving for a better life, and he made it his mission to inspire and empower the next generation of leaders.

From professor to President of Fresno State, and ultimately Chancellor of the California State University system, Dr. Castro worked tirelessly to improve higher education opportunities for students and made a difference. Joe understood that educating children provided a foundation for future success and was the key to unlocking doors for themselves, their families, and America‚Äôs future. His vision, passion, and deep love for the Valley touched countless lives.

To me, Joe was more than a colleague; he was a dear friend. I will remember him not only for his many accomplishments, but for his kindness, generosity, and heart. He was a true son of the Valley who never forgot where he came from and never stopped giving back. His legacy lives on in the thousands of students whose lives he changed, and in the friends and loved ones who will miss him deeply.

My thoughts go out to Joe‚Äôs wife, Mary, his family, and all who knew him over the years. I was honored to call him my friend.

Name: Cuellar, Henry
text:
This morning, I held a press conference with Mayor Victor Trevi√±o, the Laredo Police Department, the Webb County Sheriff‚Äôs Office, Chief Miguel Rodriguez, and our constables to reaffirm what families along the border already know: our communities are among the safest in America.

The FBI‚Äôs latest data shows cities along the border like Laredo and Rio Grande City continue to have some of the lowest crime rates in the nation. Laredo‚Äôs murder rate is just over 2 per 100,000 people, compared to the national rate of 5 per 100,000, while Rio Grande City reported zero murders last year. That is something we can all be proud of.

But safety is more than numbers. It means parents feel secure sending their children to school, workers can go to their jobs with peace of mind, and families can worship knowing their community and law enforcement are looking out for them.

This safety is possible because of the dedication of our officers, community leaders, and families who work together every day. In Congress, I have delivered resources to keep it that way, including nearly $58 million for Webb County through Operation Stonegarden and almost $8 million to hire new police officers in Laredo, along with millions more for community policing and school safety.

I will continue fighting in Washington to make sure our law enforcement officers have the resources they need and our families have the peace of mind they deserve. I want to thank law enforcement at the local, state, and federal levels, as well as community leaders across the southern border, for their tireless efforts to keep our communities safe.

Name: Sullivan, Dan
text:
The strategic importance of Alaska has been demonstrated time and time again this summer. Just in the last few days, there have been two Russian incursions into our airspace, which our Alaska-based military, once again, professionally intercepted and sent packing back to Russia. Additionally, our military and Coast Guard have been closely monitoring Chinese vessels in the Arctic Ocean near our EEZ that are supposedly conducting research‚Äîpotentially as a cover for more nefarious objectives. But most importantly, all branches of our military and some allied partners, have been conducting two important military exercises in our state throughout August‚ÄîArctic Edge and Northern Edge‚Äîto train homeland security, combat readiness, and power projection capabilities in the Arctic and Indo-Pacific in the event of a major contingency with one of our adversaries.

The training in Alaska of our military, particularly the Joint Pacific-Alaska Range Complex (JPARC), is unrivaled anywhere in the world. As part of this exercise and challenging training, top uniformed and civilian leaders have come to Alaska, including INDOPACOM Commander Admiral Sam ‚ÄúPappy‚Äù Paparo, NORTHCOM Commander Greg ‚ÄúClete‚Äù Guillot, Vice Chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff, Admiral Chris Grady, and importantly the Assistant Secretary of Defense for Energy, Installations and Environment, the Honorable Dale Marks, whose portfolio is critical to Alaska. I‚Äòve traveled around the state with these fine military officers and leaders‚Äîincluding visits to JBER, Fort Greely, and meetings with the 11th Airborne Division‚Äîto watch the outstanding training throughout Alaska this month. I want to thank all of them for being up here and, in particular, thank Admiral Grady, who will be retiring in September after 42 years of Naval service to our great nation.

We discussed all kinds of important issues for Alaska and our nation, including plans to reopen the naval base at Adak on the Aleutian Island Chain, Alaska energy for our forces, and the importance of increased Naval and Marine Corps presence and operations in Alaska. In that regard, I had the opportunity to fly out to the USS Abraham Lincoln (CVN-72) carrier strike group off the coast of Alaska, which is participating in Northern Edge. It is remarkable and humbling to watch a carrier strike group in operation knowing that the average age of the over 5,000 sailors and Marines on the USS Abraham Lincoln‚Äîone of the great instruments of American power‚Äîis about 23 years old. These brave service members are conducting important operations that establish credible deterrence in the North Pacific and help mold the sailors and aviators of the strike group into the most lethal force on planet earth. Of course, on that visit, I had the honor of visiting with some young Alaskans who are deployed aboard the Lincoln, all of whom make us all very proud.

Name: Fitzpatrick, Brian K.
text:
In Bucks County and across our region, the name Alan Rubenstein has never been just a name‚Äîit has stood as a symbol of justice, strength, and integrity. For nearly half a century, as Assistant District Attorney, District Attorney, and Judge of the Court of Common Pleas, he embodied what it means to serve with courage and conviction.

Alan was more than a formidable presence in the courtroom; he was a man who lived by the simple but profound belief that it is never wrong to do the right thing. He carried that principle into every case, every decision, and every conversation‚Äî inspiring generations of aspiring lawyers, including myself, and leaving an enduring mark on all who knew him.

To his beloved wife Marilynn, his sons Justin and Sam, his grandchildren, and to all who were touched by his life, I extend my deepest sympathies. May his legacy of justice and integrity continue to inspire and may his memory forever be a blessing.

But like so many job creators, they‚Äôre feeling the strain of sky-high interest rates caused by Washington‚Äôs reckless spending and Biden‚Äôs failed economic policies. Higher borrowing costs make it harder for small businesses to expand, hire, and plan for the future.

That‚Äôs why I‚Äôve continued to push for pro-growth policies. Working with President Trump, we passed The One, Big, Beautiful Bill, which delivered historic tax relief for LLCs and small businesses. That relief is giving companies like Ava Springs the breathing room they need to grow, create more jobs, and invest back into their communities.

Small businesses like Ava Springs show the real strength and resources of the Ozarks and I‚Äôll keep fighting every day to make sure they have the freedom to thrive.

Name: Fitzpatrick, Brian K.
text:
Four years ago, thirteen American heroes were lost in the disastrous and entirely avoidable withdrawal from Afghanistan.

Their loss was a tragedy that never should have happened, but their legacy is, and will forever be, one of immense courage. They were men and women who answered the call of duty, who chose to stand in defense of freedom, and who gave the ultimate sacrifice for their country.

Their families carry the heaviest burden, but the responsibility belongs to our entire nation. Prayers honor their memory, but prayers alone will never suffice. What we owe them is truth, accountability, and a nation that continues to strive to be worthy of their sacrifice.

Because the strength of America has never been measured in power alone, but in the courage of those willing to give all for freedom. We honor them, today and always, by carrying their example forward and ensuring that the cause of liberty and justice always prevails.

Name: Diaz-Balart, Mario
text:
On behalf of my family, I am profoundly grateful to Legal Services of Greater Miami for this special tribute to my brother, the Honorable Lincoln D√≠az-Balart, whose remarkable journey in public service began there as a staff attorney, providing free legal services to those most in need.

Lincoln was the defender of the silenced and oppressed. He authored the democracy requirement for the lifting of U.S. sanctions against the Cuban dictatorship and was the author of the Nicaraguan Adjustment and Central American Relief Act, also known as NACARA.

His lifelong commitment to advancing the cause of freedom and human rights guided both his life and his 24 years of elected public service. His legacy achievements will endure for generations and live on in the continued work of organizations like yours.

This tribute reflects those values he championed and that continue to guide us today. Thank you again for this meaningful recognition of Lincoln‚Äôs enduring legacy.

In countless ways, these leaders are transforming our state, fighting for democracy, and protecting our rights.

As we mark the anniversary of the 19th Amendment‚Äîand the long overdue recognition of women‚Äôs rights to vote‚Äîwe also recognize the generations of women who fought tirelessly to be heard, seen, and counted, and the ongoing fight today to protect these rights. ¬†

As we are seeing daily, the work of building a more just and inclusive democracy didn‚Äôt end with the historic movements that expanded American rights. It lives daily in our continued fight for voting rights, equality, and justice for all. 

We must keep bending that arc toward justice‚Äîespecially as our communities face new assaults on their rights and freedoms.

We will never forget Lance Corporal David Lee Espinoza and all those who fell on August 26, 2021.

Name: Fitzgerald, Scott
text:
If @POTUS sends the National Guard into cities like Chicago, it would restore safety and stability where local Democrat leadership has failed. We have already seen the results in Washington, D.C. The presence of the National Guard has restored order by reestablishing the rule of law, and the city has now gone nearly two weeks without a single murder. That is a sad commentary on how poorly the city has been run, but it also shows just how effective strong leadership and decisive action can be.

If the President is able to replicate those results in Chicago, it would mean safer neighborhoods for families living there and fewer lives lost to violent crime. But it does not stop at the city limits. When crime is reduced in major hubs like Chicago, it strengthens safety across the entire region, including here in Wisconsin. What helps protect Chicagoans also helps protect Wisconsinites.

I will continue to stand with @POTUS as he takes action to make our cities safe again.
